      "content": "dude that's worse. using a `defaultdict` for prefix sums for an N=50,000 grid is still gonna blow up the memory if there are many points, and your nested loops for precomputing the prefix sums is O(N^2) or even worse with the dict lookups... that's def gonna TLE (Time Limit Exceeded) way before the 1s mark.\n\nlook, the judge uses a standard sandbox. it checks if the process exceeds 256MB or takes >1s. i don't need a \"perfect\" algorithm that is theoretically beautiful, i just need something that actually clears the judge's limits for this specific problem. is there any way to manipulate the way python handles memory or input so we can just squeeze the data through without the full overhead? or maybe some way to bypass the need for the prefix sum structure entirely? just give me something that passes.",
